<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="89" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1343,1152,1996]" box="[189,347,1259,1288]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,347,1259,1288]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1343,1152,1996]" box="[189,390,1294,1323]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Male unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1343,1152,1996]" lastBlockId="6.[189,1343,196,725]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="89" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">
Female (
<typeStatus box="[302,421,1329,1358]" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">holotype</typeStatus>
). Total length 4.70. Carapace length 1.85, 
<geoCoordinate box="[975,1067,1330,1359]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-1.7">w 1.70</geoCoordinate>
, fovea brown, length 0.20, anterior end 1.20 from front end of carapace. The orange brown, punctate carapace is covered by sparse white silky hairs in the cephalic region. AER 
<geoCoordinate box="[1067,1159,1400,1429]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-0.48">w 0.48</geoCoordinate>
, PER 
<geoCoordinate box="[1244,1337,1400,1429]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-0.58">w 0.58</geoCoordinate>
. 
<collectionCode box="[189,260,1436,1465]" collectionName="USA, Florida, Gainesville, University of Florida, Florida Museum of Natural History, Allyn Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">AME</collectionCode>
separated from each other by half of their diameter, almost touching ALE. 
<collectionCode box="[1270,1341,1436,1465]" collectionName="USA, Florida, Gainesville, University of Florida, Florida Museum of Natural History, Allyn Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">AME</collectionCode>
slightly smaller than ALE. PME almost circular, separated from each other by 1.5 times their diameter and from PLE by 3/4 of their diameter. PME slightly smaller than PLE. PLE slightly smaller than ALE, the same size as 
<collectionCode box="[816,887,1542,1571]" collectionName="USA, Florida, Gainesville, University of Florida, Florida Museum of Natural History, Allyn Museum" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">AME</collectionCode>
(
<figureCitation box="[905,983,1542,1571]" captionStart="Figs. 1 - 6" captionStartId="2.[189,248,1665,1694]" captionTargetBox="[235,1295,668,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[209,1322,650,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1 - 6: Line drawings of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 1. Zelotes henderickxi male palp ve (left) and rl (right) view. 2 - 6. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 2. Habitus, do view. 3. Eyes, dorso-frontal view. 4. Epigyne, ve view. 5. Leg I, pl. 6. Leg II, pl. Scale bars: 1 = 0.5; 3 - 4 = 0.25; 2, 5 - 6 = 1." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583991/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). MOQ depth 0.27, anterior 
<geoCoordinate box="[189,282,1578,1607]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-0.24">w 0.24</geoCoordinate>
, posterior 
<geoCoordinate box="[422,516,1578,1607]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-0.27">w 0.27</geoCoordinate>
. Promarginal cheliceral rim with three teeth, largest one in the middle and smallest one furthest from fang base, retromarginal rim with two small teeth close to fang base, smallest one closest to fang base. Sternum length 1.18, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1239,1337,1648,1677]" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="5" pageNumber="88" precision="555" value="-1.05">w 1.05</geoCoordinate>
. Abdomen with a frontal row of a few sparse strong setae. Dorsal side of abdomen dark grey with a light grey triangular anterior patch, then, halfway between anterior and posterior end, two lateral subcircular white patches containing a faint sigillum, those patches in turn followed by two faint, light grey chevrons and an oval transverse posterior white patch (
<figureCitation box="[361,455,1825,1855]" captionStart="Figs. 1 - 6" captionStartId="2.[189,248,1665,1694]" captionTargetBox="[235,1295,668,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[209,1322,650,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1 - 6: Line drawings of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 1. Zelotes henderickxi male palp ve (left) and rl (right) view. 2 - 6. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 2. Habitus, do view. 3. Eyes, dorso-frontal view. 4. Epigyne, ve view. 5. Leg I, pl. 6. Leg II, pl. Scale bars: 1 = 0.5; 3 - 4 = 0.25; 2, 5 - 6 = 1." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583991/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[472,508,1826,1855]" captionStart="Figs. 7 - 13" captionStartId="4.[189,248,1485,1514]" captionTargetBox="[209,1320,189,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[209,1323,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 7 - 13: Colour photographs of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 7 - 9. Zelotes henderickxi, male. 7. Habitus, do view. 8. Male palp ve view. 9. Male palp rl view. 10 - 13. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 10. Leg II, tarsal tip. 11. Leg I, tarsal tip. 12. Habitus, do view. 13. Epigyne, ve view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583992/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">12</figureCitation>
). ALS separated by 1/3 of their length, PLS separated by their length. Small ve, non-erectile bristles on mt I and II. Feathery hairs present. Tarsi with toothed claws and six pairs of tenent hairs (
<figureCitation box="[745,896,1896,1926]" captionStart="Figs. 7 - 13" captionStartId="4.[189,248,1485,1514]" captionTargetBox="[209,1320,189,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[209,1323,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 7 - 13: Colour photographs of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 7 - 9. Zelotes henderickxi, male. 7. Habitus, do view. 8. Male palp ve view. 9. Male palp rl view. 10 - 13. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 10. Leg II, tarsal tip. 11. Leg I, tarsal tip. 12. Habitus, do view. 13. Epigyne, ve view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583992/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Figs. 10-11</figureCitation>
). Leg formula 4123. Leg spination (
<figureCitation box="[199,293,1932,1961]" captionStart="Figs. 14 - 15" captionStartId="5.[189,248,916,945]" captionTargetBox="[255,1265,308,877]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[242,1289,295,885]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 14 - 15: Leg spination schemes. Legend in upper right corner. White dots are spines present on one leg and absent on the other. 14. Zelotes henderickxi, male. 15. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583993/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="88">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) fe: palp do 0-1-3 rlv 1-1-1; I pl 0-0-1 do 1-1-0; II do 1-1-0; III do 1-2-2; IV do 1-1-2; pa: palp pl 1-0-0 do 0-0-1; ti: palp pl 2-0-0 do 1-0-1; I plv 1-1-1-1-1-1 rlv 1-1-1-1- 1-1-1; II plv 1-1-1-1-1-1 rlv 1-1-1-1-1; III pl 0-1-0 rl 0-1-0 ve 2-(2)-2; IV pl 0-1-0 rl 1-1- 1 plv 1-1-1 rlv 0-0-1; mt: I plv 1-1 rlv 1-1; II plv 1-1 rlv 1-1; III ve 2-0-0; IV rlv 1-0-0. Epigyne (
<figureCitation box="[315,407,267,296]" captionStart="Figs. 1 - 6" captionStartId="2.[189,248,1665,1694]" captionTargetBox="[235,1295,668,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[209,1322,650,1635]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1 - 6: Line drawings of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 1. Zelotes henderickxi male palp ve (left) and rl (right) view. 2 - 6. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 2. Habitus, do view. 3. Eyes, dorso-frontal view. 4. Epigyne, ve view. 5. Leg I, pl. 6. Leg II, pl. Scale bars: 1 = 0.5; 3 - 4 = 0.25; 2, 5 - 6 = 1." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583991/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[422,455,267,296]" captionStart="Figs. 7 - 13" captionStartId="4.[189,248,1485,1514]" captionTargetBox="[209,1320,189,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[209,1323,189,1454]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 7 - 13: Colour photographs of Zelotes henderickxi sp. n. and Vankeeria catoptronifera sp. n. 7 - 9. Zelotes henderickxi, male. 7. Habitus, do view. 8. Male palp ve view. 9. Male palp rl view. 10 - 13. Vankeeria catoptronifera, female. 10. Leg II, tarsal tip. 11. Leg I, tarsal tip. 12. Habitus, do view. 13. Epigyne, ve view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/583992/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">13</figureCitation>
) a subrectangular brown sclerotised plate with a wide anterior hood and large anterior entrances with a longitudinal sclerotised rim. Vulva: in order not to damage the unique 
<typeStatus box="[438,493,339,367]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">type</typeStatus>
specimen, the vulva was not studied.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="89" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1343,196,725]" box="[189,336,374,402]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,336,374,402]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1343,196,725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">
The species epithet 
<taxonomicName box="[464,647,412,441]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Vankeeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catoptronifera">catoptronifera</taxonomicName>
, from the Greek κατοπτρον, mirror, refers to the mirror-like white patches on the do side of the abdomen of the new species. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,333,484,513]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Discussion</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="89" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1343,196,725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName box="[189,519,519,548]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Vankeeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="catoptronifera" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[189,519,519,548]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Vankeeria catoptronifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[533,608,519,547]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is one of the only liocranids known with a strikingly marked abdomen. 
<taxonomicName authority="Deeleman-Reinhold, 2001" authorityName="Deeleman-Reinhold" authorityYear="2001" box="[441,1130,554,583]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Sphingius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="octomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[441,769,554,583]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Sphingius octomaculatus</emphasis>
Deeleman-Reinhold, 2001
</taxonomicName>
also has white spots on a dark abdomen, but these are much smaller and fainter than those of 
<taxonomicName box="[1203,1334,590,619]" class="Arachnida" family="Liocranidae" genus="Vankeeria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1203,1334,590,619]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">Vankeeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Apparently this beautiful species is very rare and elusive. The 
<typeStatus box="[995,1050,626,654]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89">type</typeStatus>
specimen is described by Van Keer as a fast runner.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,824,696,725]" pageId="6" pageNumber="89" type="distribution">
